paragraphs.title: Spark ETL
paragraphs.text:
%spark

import java.sql.Timestamp
import java.text.SimpleDateFormat

val divvyDateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat("MM/dd/yyyy hh:mm")

def makeTimestamp(ts: String) = {new java.sql.Timestamp(divvyDateFormat.parse(ts).getTime())}
    

val rawRidesRDD = sc.textFile("file:///home/trevor/gits/data/divvy_data/*.csv")
val header = rawRidesRDD.first()
val ridesRDD = rawRidesRDD.filter(_ != header)



case class Ride(trip_id: Int,
                starttime: Timestamp,
                stoptime: Timestamp,
                bikeid: Int,
                tripduration: Int,
                from_station_id: Int,
                from_station_name: String,
                to_station_id: Int,
                to_station_name: String,
                usertype: String,
                gender: String,
                birthyear: Int)

val ridesDF = ridesRDD.map(line => line.split(","))
                        .filter(_.length > 10)
                        .map( l =>  Ride(l(0).toInt, 
                                        makeTimestamp(l(1)),
                                        makeTimestamp(l(2)), 
                                        l(3).toInt, 
                                        l(4).toInt, 
                                        l(5).toInt, 
                                        l(6), 
                                        l(7).toInt, 
                                        l(8), 
                                        l(9), 
                                        l(10), 
                                        l(11).toInt  )).toDF()
                                                                    
ridesDF.registerTempTable("divvy_rides")

paragraphs.text:
%md

## Business Problem: Overtime Trips

**Background** Divvy charges customers an overage fee if the trip lasts longer than 30 minutes. 

**Task** We want to be able to predict when a customer is going to rent longer than 30 minutes so that we might send them an alert when they check out the bike reminding them of the 30 minute time window. 

**Conditions** Because people don't (*shouldn't*) be on their phone while riding their bike, we need to send this message as soon as possible.  We are hoping to take advantage of Flink's lower latency / higher through put for our production system, so while exploratory analysis may be done in Spark, we would like a solution utilizing Flink.


### Approach

First, we make a pivot chart for Spark to do some exploratory analysis. We'll use screen shots of interesting findings for sales, and export the entire chart as a 'working toy' for the sales reps to use in the pitch.

Second, we'll ETL data into Flink and run a multi-layer perceptron on it.  Our reasoning for doing this is that this entire example is **_completely_** contrived anyway and we want to show how dependencies can be loaded in Flink.

Finally, we'll try to come up with some additional visualizatoin that add questionable business value but looks super sexy to once again support sales guys and because our bonuses are calculated based on our *sizzle factor*.  If I had to guess, I'd say it's going to be a community-detection thing feeding into a d3js.

Business Problem: Overtime Trips

Background Divvy charges customers an overage fee if the trip lasts longer than 30 minutes.

Task We want to be able to predict when a customer is going to rent longer than 30 minutes so that we might send them an alert when they check out the bike reminding them of the 30 minute time window.

Conditions Because people don't (shouldn't) be on their phone while riding their bike, we need to send this message as soon as possible. We are hoping to take advantage of Flink's lower latency / higher through put for our production system, so while exploratory analysis may be done in Spark, we would like a solution utilizing Flink.

Approach

First, we make a pivot chart for Spark to do some exploratory analysis. We'll use screen shots of interesting findings for sales, and export the entire chart as a 'working toy' for the sales reps to use in the pitch.

Second, we'll ETL data into Flink and run a multi-layer perceptron on it. Our reasoning for doing this is that this entire example is completely contrived anyway and we want to show how dependencies can be loaded in Flink.

Finally, we'll try to come up with some additional visualizatoin that add questionable business value but looks super sexy to once again support sales guys and because our bonuses are calculated based on our sizzle factor. If I had to guess, I'd say it's going to be a community-detection thing feeding into a d3js.

paragraphs.title: Deep Dive Pivot: Overtime trips
paragraphs.text:
%sql

select 
from_station_id, 
gender, usertype, hourOfDay, dayOfWeek, count(trip_id) as trips
from 
(select trip_id, 
tripduration, from_station_id, gender, usertype, hour(starttime) as hourOfDay,
date_format(starttime, 'EEE') as dayOfWeek -- only in 1.5+
from divvy_rides
where tripduration > (60*30) ) a
where dayOfWeek= '${dayOfWeek=Wed,Sun|Mon|Tue|Wed|Thu|Fri|Sat}'
 --and usertype= '${userType=Subscriber,Subscriber|Dependent|Customer}'
group by gender, usertype, dayOfWeek, hourOfDay ,from_station_id --, to_station_id
having trips > 1
--order by stoptime asc

paragraphs.text:
%flink
import org.apache.flink.ml.common.LabeledVector
import org.apache.flink.ml.math.SparseVector

import java.sql.Timestamp
import java.text.SimpleDateFormat

val divvyDateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat("MM/dd/yyyy hh:mm")

def makeTimestamp(ts: String) = {new java.sql.Timestamp(divvyDateFormat.parse(ts).getTime())}

val rawRides = env.readTextFile("file:///home/trevor/gits/data/divvy_data")

val headlessRides = rawRides.map(line => line.split(",")).filter(line => line(0) != "trip_id")

val ridesLV = headlessRides.filter(_.length == 12)
                            .map(l => LabeledVector( l(4).toInt match {
                                                                case d if d > 30 => 1.0
                                                                case _ => 0.0
                                                            },      // ride over 30 minutes
                                                    SparseVector(
                                                        24+7+511+3+4+1,
                                                        Array( makeTimestamp(l(1)).getHours,
                                                                        24 + makeTimestamp(l(1)).getDay, 
                                                                        24 + 7 + l(5).toInt,
                                                                        24 + 7 + 511 + (l(9) match {
                                                                            case "Male" => 0
                                                                            case "Female" => 1
                                                                            case _ => 2
                                                                        }),
                                                                        24 + 7 + 511 + 3),
                                                        Array(1.0, // hours
                                                                    1.0, 
                                                                    1.0, // station,
                                                                    1.0, // gender,
                                                                    (2016 - l(11).toInt).toDouble )
                                                                    )
                                                    )
                                            
                                            
                                ).first(500) // bc the JVM heap keeps crashing

paragraphs.title: Dark Magic- Residual Error in MLP on Divvy Bike Data
paragraphs.text:
%flink

import org.apache.flink.ml.optimization.SimpleGradientDescent
import org.apache.flink.ml.optimization.LearningRateMethod

// These are not official-supported features! Use them in production, and may ___ have mercy on your soul.
import org.apache.flink.ml.preprocessing.Splitter
import org.apache.flink.ml.neuralnetwork.MultiLayerPerceptron
import org.apache.flink.ml.evaluation.{RegressionScores, Scorer}


val dataSets = Splitter.trainTestSplit(ridesLV)


val arch = List( 10, 10)

val macroIters = 10
val microIters = 10

val loss = RegressionScores.squaredLoss
val scorer = new Scorer(loss)

val mlp_xu =  MultiLayerPerceptron()

mlp_xu.setOptimizer( SimpleGradientDescent()
                        .setIterations(microIters)
                        .setStepsize(1.0)
                        .setLearningRateMethod(LearningRateMethod.Xu(-0.75))
                        .setWarmStart(true)).setHiddenLayerArchitecture(arch)

val evaluationIcDS = dataSets.training.map(x => (x.vector, x.label))
val evaluationOocDS = dataSets.testing.map(x => (x.vector, x.label))

println("%table\nIteration\tXuSSR_SimpleSGD_inCore\tXuSSR_SimpleSGD_outOfCore\n")
for (i <- 1 to macroIters){
    mlp_xu.fit(ridesLV)
    val mseXuIC = scorer.evaluate(evaluationIcDS, mlp_xu).collect().head
    val mseXuOC = scorer.evaluate(evaluationOocDS, mlp_xu).collect().head
    println(s"${(microIters*i).toString}\t${mseXuIC.toString}\t${mseXuOC.toString}")
}

## Magical Hand Waving

I'm having a hard time wrestling with JVM heap sizes and making this run in any sane amount of time on VirtualBox, so if you look a couple of paragraphs back you'll see I clipped the dataset down to 500. 

I really just wanted to show off that you can do weird things like load your own custom ML library (I used Flink, Spark is easier. Zeppelin is a lot more Spark supported).

As of 4/26/2015- Flink Streaming Support for the Scala Shell has been added to master, but there is a regression which crashes it. 

A more realistic use case for Flink/Spark side by would be to take advantage of Flink's CEP and have a Spark App / notebook "watching" variables Flink is writing to the resource Pool.

I may have a demo of this by ApacheCon if
- The PR fixing it gets merged in to flink/master
- OR I can merge the PR fixing it myself locally 
- AND I update the flink interpretter (which I've already done, so shouldn't be a big deal)

## Another cool thing to do: Graph Analysis of Divvy Bikes
